Iam aware that the water of these thermal springs immediately beooms white if salt of tamar, or a simply saline volatile salt, be put into it, as was already remarked. But this white colour is mused ΒΥ the precipitation not of sulphur hut of a certain stony or aluminous matter, just as happens to water which has slaked quicklime when any fixed salt is mixed with it, though it is not to be supposed that sulphur is dissolved in it. For if sulphur were hoiled in the water in which quicklime has been slaked, the water would not become white, as before, on the addition of lixed salt, hut would do so on the addition of aeid. So that fixed salts appear manifestly to be fitted for dissolving sulphur hut not for precipitating it. Wherefore if the waters of the thermal springs were imbued with sulphur, they would not be precipitated as they are bya simply saline salt but ΒΥ an aeid. And indeed the sulphur precipitated by them would manifest itself hya fetid odour, but this does not at all happen.

I further add that some aeid or aluminous salt seems to preponderate in these thermal waters‚ so that they are quite incapahle ol dissolving sulphur. Nay, if common sulphur be hoiled in the said waters‚ these waters will not beat all tinged with the yellow colour of sulphur, nor can sulphur be precipitated in any way from the said decoction, as I have found by repeated trials. And indeed I am greatly surprised that the distinguished Willis in his Treatise on the Heat of the Blood, has asserted that sulphur can be dissolved when boiled in the water of the said thermal springs, just as in water that has slaked quicklime.
